                <h2>How Often Should You Use Rice Water?</h2>
                <p>Frequency is a crucial factor that many people get wrong. <strong>Using rice water once or twice a week</strong> is ideal for most hair types. Here is a general guideline:</p>

                <p><strong>Fine or thin hair:</strong> Once a week, using the soaking method. <strong>Normal hair:</strong> Once or twice a week, using the soaking or fermented method. <strong>Thick or coarse hair:</strong> Twice a week, using the boiling or fermented method. <strong>Damaged or chemically treated hair:</strong> Once a week with the soaking method, always followed by a deep conditioner.</p>

                <p>Overuse is the most common mistake people make with rice water. Because it is rich in protein, using it too frequently can lead to <strong>protein overload</strong>, which makes hair feel stiff, straw-like, and prone to snapping. If you notice these symptoms, take a break from rice water for two weeks and focus on moisture-based treatments instead.</p>

                <h2>Side Effects and Who Should Avoid Rice Water</h2>
                <p>While rice water is generally safe, it is not suitable for everyone. Here are some potential side effects and precautions:</p>

                <p><strong>Protein Overload:</strong> As mentioned, too much protein can make hair brittle. If your hair already has adequate protein, rice water may do more harm than good. <strong>Scalp Irritation:</strong> Fermented rice water, in particular, can cause irritation for those with sensitive scalps. Always do a patch test before your first use. <strong>Unpleasant Odour:</strong> Fermented rice water has a strong, sour smell. Adding a few drops of essential oil like lavender or rosemary can help mask this.</p>

                <p><strong>Who should avoid rice water:</strong> Individuals with low-porosity hair should be cautious, as the protein in rice water may sit on the surface of the hair and cause buildup rather than being absorbed. People with scalp conditions like eczema or psoriasis should consult a dermatologist before trying rice water treatments.</p>

                <h2>Beyond Rice Water: When You Need Professional Treatment</h2>
